body: $TNT Hey fellas I'm curious about something.
In the U.S. our tax system rewards investors who hold long term by giving us very favorable capital gains rates if the hold is one year or longer. It also discourages selling at a loss
created_at: then buying back within 30 days of the sale (wash sale rule). This is for standard brokerage accounts of course. We also have tax sheltered retirement accounts which allow us to trade freely within without tax consequences. But I'm curious if Canada has a similar tax regime in regard to standard brokerage account trading? What are your capital gains taxes like?
